fields.question: What is Umeqo?
fields.answer: Umeqo is an innovative recruiting resource for students and employers to discover one another by leveraging the familiar paradigms of resumes and events. The platform empowers employers to easily filter and search student profiles, create resume books, reach out to candidates, and post and manage campus events. Within minutes, students can create their easy-to-maintain profile, find and RSVP to employer events, and subscribe to employers of their choosing for future event updates.

fields.question: As a student, do I have to use my Athena password to register?
fields.answer: No, you can use whichever password you want. Our system is totally separate from anything that currently exists at MIT.

fields.question: The registration form says that I am not a student - why can I not register?
fields.answer:
There are a few possible reasons for why you cannot register.

The first is that you are not a student. The student side of Umeqo is for students only. This means that employers, affiliates, group lists, professors and alumni are all not eligible to register as students.

The second possiblity is that you are a freshman or a student taking a temporary leave from MIT. For these reasons, you may be marked as an affiliate in the MIT database. If this is so, please contact us.

Overall, judge for yourself as to whether recruiters should be able to see you alongside other students, and let us know of your situation.

fields.question: What is the difference between a public and private event?
fields.answer: Anyone can view, RSVP and is welcome to attend a public event. A private event, however, is only visible to those students who are personally invited to it by the host employer.

fields.question: Why should I create yet another profile?
fields.answer: Umeqo is the quickest, easiest way to stay on top of recruiter on-campus activity and get your resume in front of top firms. Beyond simply viewing your profile, recruiters can personally invite you to both public and private events, add you to custom resumebooks, and leave notes about you for their company's internal use. You can sign up by clicking here.

fields.question: Why was Umeqo created?
fields.answer: Umeqo was created by current MIT undergraduates to fix the pains of recruiting at MIT.  We were frustrated about missing recruiting events because we didn’t hear about them and having to drop our resumes in a gazillion different places. Building on our experiences helping employers recruit, we thus developed Umeqo to solve these problems.

fields.question: If a campus organization I’m involved in is not currently listed, what can I do?
fields.answer: To create a new campus organization, go to the third step of the profile form and click the "Don't see your campus organization? Submit yours to the list." link on the right of the fields.

fields.question: Where did the title Umeqo come from and how is it pronounced?
fields.answer: The word is Zulu for "leap". It is pronounced [you-me-co], as in you + me + company.

fields.question: Who can see my profile?
fields.answer: Your profile information is viewable only to recruiters that use Umeqo. No other students or campus organizations can view anything but your name, email and school year.

fields.question: Why do I keep getting redirected back to the create profile page when I click the "Browse Event" and "Browse Employers" links?
fields.answer: In order to start using those features, you need to fill out the required parts of your profile. These are just the field on the first tab of the create profile page.

fields.question: I can't remember my login email.
fields.answer: The login email is typically the one that you use most often. For students, it's your MIT email. For campus orgs, it's the public version of your email address (e.g. traders@mit.edu, sbc@mit.edu). For recruiters, it's your work email.

fields.question: Why are there only 14 employers?
fields.answer: The included 14 employers are the ones who are test-driving the recruiter side of Umeqo. Rest assured though, this list will grow tremendously in the next few months!

fields.question: Can students see the comments that I leave about them? Do they know whether I starred them or not?
fields.answer: Student cannot see the comments - they are only for your internal use, as are the stars. The only feedback that the students get is in the form of a set of aggregate statistics with no mention of any individual company. All your activity on the site is private and none of it is tracked.

fields.question: Can you send me a copy of my password without resetting it?
fields.answer: For security reasons, Umeqo does not have the ability to send you a copy of your current password. However, you can always reset it on the password reset page.

fields.question: How do I change my login email address?
fields.answer: You need to contact us and let us know what you would it changed to. Note that recruiters can make additional credentials for their co-workers using the "Create New Account" link on the "Account Settings" page.

fields.question: It looks like things are broken. Am I doing something wrong?
fields.answer: No, you are not. But you might be using an old browser. If this is so, please let us know of what is broken by clicking contact us in the footer for any page, and/or upgrade to the latest version of Firefox or Chrome. Or at the very least IE9. We appreciate your patience while we make the site work with older browsers!

fields.question: Why am I hitting a page with the Terms of Service when I log in?
fields.answer: Whenever we make any changes to our terms of service, we want you to be aware of them. Thus, in all future cases, we will summarize the changes at the top of the terms of service page and redirect you to it when you log in to review the changes. The button to accept will always be at the bottom.

fields.question: Can I send multiple invitations out at once?
fields.answer:
Yes! Just checkbox the students whom you want to invite and hit "Send Invite" in the "More Actions" dropdown above the student results. Then pick the event to which you want to invite students to and add a custom invite message. 

Note that you can invite a maximum of 50 students to any single event or deadline. We also advise recruiters to invite students one by one in order to include more personalized invite messages. This makes it more likely that the student will actually take the time to RSVP.

fields.question: I deactivated my account. How do I reactivate it?
fields.answer: If you deactivated your account, you can reactivate it at any time simply by logging in with your login email address and password.

fields.question: I saw an event page that had a map included along with the location! How come mine doesn't have one?
fields.answer: When you go to create your event, you will see suggestions showing up below the location field as you type in the location. You can click the down arrow on your keyboard to cycle through them and hit enter once you find the right one. This will add a map to your event!

fields.description:
The MIT Program in Writing and Humanistic Studies gives students the opportunity to learn the techniques, forms, and traditions of several kinds of writing, from basic expository prose to more advanced forms of non-fictional prose, fiction and poetry, science writing, scientific and technical communication and digital media. Our FACULTY consists of novelists, essayists, poets, translators, biographers, historians, engineers and scientists.
 
Program subjects are arranged by three areas: creative writing, science writing and digital media. In each area introductory subjects lead to more specialized advanced subjects. A number of the advanced subjects use writing as a vehicle to explore humanistic and scientific issues in a broad cultural context.
 
Students pursuing a humanities concentration in writing or a minor in writing work mainly within one of the Program's three curricular areas. Students may also major in writing or develop a joint major with another discipline in the humanities or with the Program in Science, Technology, and Society.
 
The Graduate Program in Science Writing is a 12-month course of study leading to a Master of Science degree. Aimed at students who wish to write about science and technology for general readers, the program is built around an intensive two-semester advanced science writing seminar. In addition, students choose one elective each semester, write a substantial thesis, and complete an internship. Links to other MIT programs and departments, such as the Knight Science Journalism Fellowships program, Comparative Media Studies (CMS) and the Program in Science, Technology and Society (STS) provide rich resources for students who come to the Graduate Program in Science Writing from a variety of backgrounds.
